sentences.l:
The Battler made-straight to his lodging;
as-soon-as he-arrived at the door, he-found-it well shut,
for fear of-the king Alfons, for thus it they-had-arranged:
that if not it he-should-break, that not to-him-it they-should-open for anything.

sentences.t:
Aguijó mio Çid, a la puerta se llegaua,
sacó el pie del estribera, una ferídal dava;
non se abre la puerta, ca bien era çerrada.

sentences.l:
Spurred my Çid, to the door himself he-drew,
drew-out the foot from-the stirrup, a blow-to-it he-gave;
not itself opens the door, for well it-was shut.

sentences.t:
Non vos osariemos abrir nin coger por nada;
si non, perderiemos los averes e las casas,
e [aun] demás los ojos de las caras.

sentences.l:
Not you we-would-dare to-open nor to-take-in for anything;
if not, we-would-lose the goods and the houses,
and even besides the eyes of the faces.

sentences.t:
Partiós dela puerta, por Burgos aguijaua,
llegó a Santa María, luego descavalga;
fincó los inojos, de coraçón rogava.

sentences.l:
He-parted-himself from-the door, through Burgos he-spurred,
he-came to Santa María, straightway he-dismounts;
he-planted the knees, from heart he-prayed.

sentences.t:
Mio Çid [Roy] Díaz, el que en buen[a] çinxo espada,
posó en la glera quando nol coge nadi en casa;
derredor dél una buena conpaña.

sentences.l:
My Çid Roy Díaz, the-one who in a-good (hour) girded sword,
camped on the gravel-bank since not-him takes-in nobody in house;
around him a good company.

sentences.t:
Vedada l'an conpra dentro en Burgos la casa
de todas cosas quantas son de vianda;
nol osarien vender al menos dinarada.

sentences.l:
Forbidden to-him-they-have purchase inside in Burgos the town
of all things as-many-as are of victual;
not-him they-would-dare to-sell even the least penny's-worth.
